I went hiking in Yoho, British Columbia and Jasper, Alberta this past summer, and figured this would be a great opportunity to show how you can use the Strava API to download and display hiking data.

There are N main sections to this post:

  1. Collecting your Strava data via their API
  2. Visualizing your data

Collecting Strava data via rStrava

# inspiro: https://r.iresmi.net/posts/2023/map_your_strava_activities/
pacman::p_load(rStrava, dplyr, ggplot2, ggmap, leaflet, sf, purrr)
source("secrets.R")

# create the authentication token
stoken <- httr::config(
  token = strava_oauth(
    app_name,
    app_client_id,
    app_secret,
    app_scope = "activity:read_all",
    cache = TRUE)) 
activities = stoken |> 
  get_activity_list() |> 
  compile_activities() |>
  filter(start_date_local >= as.Date("2023/07/15"),
         start_date_local <= as.Date("2023/07/23"))

gp2sf <- function(gp) {
  gp |> 
    googlePolylines::decode() |> 
    map_dfr(
      function(df) {
        df |> 
          st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat")) |> 
          st_combine() |> 
          st_cast("LINESTRING") |> 
          st_sf() 
      }) |> 
    pull(1)
}

# Plot maps of hikes
activities |> 
  
  mutate(geom = gp2sf(map.summary_polyline)) |> 
  st_sf(crs = "EPSG:4326") |> 
  leaflet() |> 
  addTiles() |> 
  addPolylines(color = "black")

Elevation Profiles

# Create a function to plot the elevation for each activity using ggplot2
plot_activity_elevation_ggplot <- function(activity_data) {
  
  tmp = get_activity_streams(act_data = activity_data, stoken = stoken)
   
  elevation_data = tmp |> 
    select(distance, altitude)
  
  ggplot(elevation_data, aes(x = distance, y = altitude)) +
    geom_line(color = "blue") +
    labs(x = "Distance (kilometers)", y = "Elevation (meters)",
         title = paste("Elevation Profile for Activity ID", unique(activity_data$name))) +
    theme_minimal()
}

# Split activities data.frame by id and apply the function to each activity
plots_list <- lapply(split(activities, activities$id), plot_activity_elevation_ggplot)

# Arrange and display the elevation profiles in a single column using facet_wrap
multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL) {
  require(gridExtra)
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)
  num_plots <- length(plots)
  grid.arrange(grobs=plots, ncol=5)
}

multiplot(plotlist = plots_list)
